title: AP English Language - 9E: Read Jhumpa Lahiri's "A Temporary Matter" (242-261)
description: A few questions to consider as you read  1) What stylistic devices does Lahiri use to show the distance between Shoba and Shukumar?  2) How does the motif of light and dark play out through this story?  3) Does gender play a role in our understanding of the text?  4) What role do secrets play in the story?

title: AP English Language - 9E: Read Ted Chiang's "The Great Silence" pgs. 432-436
description: This story is diametrically different from "A Temporary Matter." In "The Great Silence," you will see a story narrated by a parrot. This sounds ridiculous, but the story is grounded.  A few questions,  1) What is Ted Chiang saying about technology and humanity?  2) Empathy is a major theme in this essay. Who has empathy in this story? Who lacks empathy?  3) What are the parrots' views on human technological progress? What is their issue with our desire to constantly be looking off into the horizon?

title: AP English Language - 9E: Read Louise Erdrich's "The Red Convertible" pgs. 40-50
description: In Erdrich's "The Red Convertible," we see two Chippewa brothers connect via a red convertible. However, over the course of the story, we see the brothers grow apart due to changes in Stephan.   A few questions,  1) How are the brothers--Marty (the narrator) and Stephan similar? How are they different?  2) How is life on a native people's reservation represented in this story? How is it similar or dissimilar to other stories we've read?  3) What causes the change in Stephan's personality?  4) After you've read the story, how do you feel about Marty's decision at the end of the story?
